The preparation of quantum dots usually requires surface stabilizers, and glutathione (GSH) is an excellent choice.[

                        1

                     ] Glutathione is a -SH-containing tripeptide composed of L-Cys, GLU and Gly[

                        2

                     ] and is a biomolecule present in all cells. As an essential endogenous cellular antioxidant and the most abundant cellular non-protein biothiol,[

                        3

                     ] the sulfhydryl group in glutathione gives it important physiological functions such as antioxidant and detoxification,[

                        4

                     ] thus making it a potent antioxidant in cells.[

                        2

                     ] As an endogenous antioxidant,[

                        5

                     ,

                        6

                     ] glutathione is important in cellular defense against toxins, maintenance of intracellular redox homeostasis,[

                        5

                     ] detoxification,[

                        7

                     ] and metabolism.[

                        8

                     ,

                        9

                     ] Also, glutathione is a potential coating material for luminescent quantum dots.[

                        7

                     ] Silver sulfide quantum dots (Ag2S QDs) are a new class of near-infrared fluorescent quantum dots that have been widely studied for their narrow band gap, high optical absorption coefficient, and environmental friendliness.[

                        10

                     ] It is free of heavy metals,[

                        11

                     ] has low toxicity,[

                        12

                     ] good cytocompatibility,[

                        13

                     ,

                        14

                     ] high absorption coefficient,[

                        12

                     ] good chemical and photostability,[

                        15

                     ] broad absorption spectrum,[

                        12

                     ] excellent resistance to photobleaching,[

                        16

                     ] high extinction coefficient,[

                        15

                     ] and narrow band gap,[

                        17

                     ] which are properties that can be used in photocatalysis, solar cells, fluorescent sensors and bioimaging.[

                        12

                     ,

                        15

                     ,

                        17

                     ,

                        18

                     ]

Ag2S QDS were prepared by Hashemkhani M's group[

                        19

                     ] in a round bottom flask under argon atmosphere. In this study, aqueous AgNO3 solution was used as a silver source and GSH was used as a stabilizer. The emission wavelength and fluorescence intensity of Ag2S QDS were adjusted by optimizing the sulfur source as well as the temperature, time and pH value of the experiment. The experimental results showed that Ag2S QDS with small particle size, high quantum yield and good dispersion could be obtained when Na2S was used as the sulfur source, heated at 50 °C and reacted at pH 10 for 2 h, and has been successfully used for cell imaging.

In the work of Hu et al.,[

                        20

                     ] GSH-protected Ag2S QDs were synthesized by selecting GSH as stabilizer and modifier and providing S source through sulfur-hydrazine complex (S-N2H4∙H2O). GSH contains -NH2 and -COOH, so the prepared GSH-Ag2S QDs possess good dispersibility and chemical stability in aqueous solution. In addition, the fluorescence of Ag2S QDs is quenched when bisphenol A (BPA) is introduced into the Ag2S QDs. Therefore, the quantum dots can be used as a fluorescence sensing platform for specific detection of BPA.

Heavy metal ions, even at very low concentrations, still cause drinking water contamination and food safety problems that negatively affect public health.[

                        21

                     ] In the management of environmental pollution, the management of heavy metal ion pollution has become urgent. Fe3+ is the most abundant transition metal element in the earth's crust.[

                        22

                     ] As one of the transition metal ions, Fe3+ is an oxidatively active metal ion,[

                        23

                     ] which is widely present in living organisms and is an essential nutrient for them.[

                        24

                     ] In the environment and biological systems, Fe3+ plays an irreplaceable role in metabolism and energy transfer processes.[

                        25

                     ]Fe3+ can be involved in many metabolic processes such as oxygen transport, DNA biosynthesis, electron transfer, photosynthesis, and respiration.[

                        24

                     ]Fe3+ deficiency can produce various human diseases such as anemia, respiratory problems, and diabetes[

                        25–27

                     ], while excess Fe3+ can cause environmental pollution and cytotoxicity, leading to various problems. From the environmental point of view, excess Fe3+ can seriously pollute water and soil and pose a serious threat to environmental safety.[

                        27

                     ] From the human health perspective, Fe3+ excess can cause tissue or organ damage, induce hepatitis and organ dysfunction,[

                        28

                     ] which is quite harmful to human body. Therefore, the search for simple and efficient methods to detect Fe3+ is crucial for both environmental and organismal aspects.[

                        25

                     ] To date, many methods have been developed for Fe3+ detection, such as colorimetric methods,[

                        29

                     ] atomic absorption spectrometry,[

                        30

                     ] inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry,[

                        31

                     ] and fluorescence spectrometry.[

                        32

                     ] Among them, colorimetric method, atomic absorption spectrometry and inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry have the disadvantages of long test time, complicated test sample preparation and high cost of experimental equipment; therefore, fluorescence spectroscopy, which is a simple process, inexpensive, sensitive and reproducible, has been widely studied.[

                        24

                     ] Studies on the use of quantum dots as fluorescent nanoprobes for Fe3+ detection have been reported.[

                        24

                     ,

                        32

                     ]
